## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### Pattern Analysis

Your code contains three APIs that **throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 6+:

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control-flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — mirrors the old ThreadAbortException block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control whether to continue or exit.
                // The loop condition will exit on the next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(2000)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in modern .NET.
            // If this happens, your GetNextItem/ProcessItem must be
            // fixed to check the token more frequently.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Critical: Make Blocking Calls Cancellation-Aware

The old `Thread.Abort` could forcibly interrupt a blocked `GetNextItem()`. **Cooperative cancellation cannot do this.** You must pass the token into any blocking call:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until an item is available
}

// AFTER — unblocks when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If the blocking call doesn't accept a token (e.g., synchronous I/O), replace `Thread.Sleep` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne`, or switch to async I/O.

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing token through the full call chain** | If `GetNextItem` blocks without checking the token, `Stop()` will hang forever — there is no force-kill fallback. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in retry loops** | Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so cancellation wakes it immediately. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always `Dispose()` it. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated ones. |
| **Expecting instant cancellation** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `ProcessItem` if it runs long. |
| **`Thread.Join` replaced `Thread.Sleep`** | The original `Thread.Sleep(2000)` was a blind wait. `_workerThread.Join(2000)` is strictly better — it returns immediately if the thread exits early. |

### What Changed Fundamentally

**Preemptive → Cooperative:** The .NET Framework runtime would *inject* `ThreadAbortException` at arbitrary points. Modern .NET requires your code to *voluntarily check* for cancellation. If your code doesn't check, it won't stop. This is safer (no torn state) but demands that every blocking call in the chain accepts a `CancellationToken`.
